AGI - "Care girls and dear children, dear girls and dear boys! Here we go! Gmb's adventure began, World Children's Day. We have gathered here at the Olympic Stadium, to give the 'hot of beginning to a movement of children and girls who want to build a world of peace, where we are all brothers, a world that has a future, because we want to take care of the environment that surrounds us. "Beautiful world" &nbsp;says your song. Thank you for this!" Thus Pope Francis at the beginning of his speech at the Olympic Stadium in Rome for the first World Children's Day,
&nbsp;
Pope Francis arrived at the Stadium for the meeting with Children on the occasion of the first "World Day of Children" (Gmb 2024), sponsored by the Dicastery for Culture and Education. The Pontiff was welcomed by an applause and the anthem of the Gmb "We are". Francesco, in the runway of the Stadium, on board the white jeep, is&nbsp; was accompanied by six children. The Pope greeted and launched the candy to children near the track.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Is it true that peace is always possible?", is the question that Geronimo, from Colombia, addressed Pope Francis. "Peace is always possible", the Pontiff confirmed, who then asked the entire stadium crowded by children and their families: "But how do you make peace? We think at school, I have a problem with another child...", and immediately the children who are close to Francis respond and then repeat to the microphone "Forgive and apologize", "make peace". The Pope then added: "Look at how you make peace" and he held his hand to Geronimo, inviting everyone to do it with his neighbor. "This is a gesture of peace," "playing together and helping others, the world will be better." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Francis responded to a child from Nicaragua who asked him why there are so many people without home or work. "This is an injustice. Unfortunately, there are so many people who have no work, have no home, live in tents, many times have no food," "this is the fruit of malice, it is the fruit of the selfishness of war".&nbsp; "There is so much evil and so much selfishness - the Pontiff has emphasized -. Many countries spend money buying weapons and destroying and there are people who have no food." And Francis invites the children present in the Olympic Stadium in Rome to think about their peers "who have no food".
&nbsp;
"There are people who do not work - the Pope added - and this is humanity's fault. Every day pray for children who suffer this injustice." "Let us make a little silence and in this silence each think of the girls and children who have no food and pray to the Lord to help solve this injustice, of which we all have some guilt."
&nbsp;
Then Federico from Italy asked the Pope why there are so many children who suffer. "We must be all the same but it is not so," the Pontiff said. "It happens for selfishness and injustice because people are selfish and unfair. We must work so that there is no injustice in the world." &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;

